Early on in the story, it would probably be Oliver, but he would be too tactful to stare. He’d just steal lots of glances when he thinks Kogan isn’t paying attention. What do you mean?!” And Kogan would be like “you've been staring at me.” and Oliver would want to die of embarrassment, but then Kogan would say something like “if there’s a ghost behind me right now you better tell me or else." and Oliver would realize that Kogan is actually completely oblivious. On the other hand, Kogan might stare at Oli without realizing it as he tries to figure out "what is with this guy? Why is he always so nice and cheerful all the time? Doesn't he realize we're living a nightmare? And why does he keep trying to help me when I've made it perfectly clear that I think he's a nuisance? Is he just an idiot? But I've seen him be clever at times too. I wish he'd stop being so inconsistent... it's distracting and lately I can barely focus on anything else." And Oli would look up and notice Kogan staring at him with a scowl all over his face and think “oh no, what did I do this time?”

03/17/2023 at 13:53:54 PDT

"You have to have at least thought about it!" Oliver gasped. His words sound loud in the small space of the spiral staircase, where only their footsteps and heavy breathing break the silence. Well. Just Oliver's heavy breathing. Kogan hasn't even broken a sweat despite the fact that they've been climbing these stairs long enough that Oliver is pretty sure they should have reached the top of the building several times over... But to be fair, keeping track of time is getting a little difficult. It's impossible to see how much further the stairs go or how far they've come. Visibility is limited to just a few steps ahead or behind them before the stairs wrap around the thick central column and disappear. The next ring of stairs above them is close enough for Oliver to touch if he reaches up. The space isn't suffocating, but it's confining, and that feeling becomes more pronounced as time passes. And even though there's only enough room for two people to walk side by side, Oliver can't shake the feeling that they're not alone. "I don't exactly have time to worry about it," Kogan shrugs, disinterested. "You don't need *time*..." Oliver counters between labored breaths. "You just... see someone and... think about it!" Kogan tsks, "Well, who have you thought about it with, then?" he asks, shooting Oliver an accusatory look over his shoulder. Oliver nearly stumbles on the steps, "What?! No! I mean *Nobody*. I didn't...— I'm just *saying*!" Kogan eyes him suspiciously, and Oliver looks away, feeling his face grow hot. If Kogan notices, Oliver hopes he'll chalk it up to exertion. "I need to take a break," Oliver says, partly to change the subject and partly because he is well and truly exhausted. He avoids Kogan's eyes as he slumps down on one of the steps and pulls a water bottle out of his bag, taking a long drink. Kogan sighs and sits down beside Oliver. "that's the second break in the last 10 minutes." He grumbles, "We'll never reach the bottom at this rate..." That earns a chuckle from Oliver, which unfortunately causes him to choke on his water. Kogan watches with a bemused expression as Oliver recovers from a brief coughing fit, "Sorry..." he wheezes, wiping his chin on his sleeve, "you said bottom." Kogan gives him a withering look, "What are you talking about?" Oliver clears his throat, "I think you mean *top*." Kogan's frown only deepens. Oliver lifts his gaze away with a shake of his head, "I guess this place is getting to you too." Kogan turns to face Oliver fully. "Are you telling me you think we've been walking up the stairs all this time?" Kogan asks in the slow, deliberate tone he always uses when he thinks Oliver is being dense. "Uh... Yeah?" Oliver glances over to see Kogan looking at him with narrowed eyes. A feeling of unease begins to settle over him. Kogan nods thoughtfully to himself. "I thought you were just out of shape..." Oliver sputters indignantly, but Kogan is already speaking again in a distant kind of voice, "Could it be an illusion? Like those that spin in two directions, depending on how you look at them..." "...What are you trying to say?" Oliver asks in disbelief, "That we've really been going down all this time?" Kogan looks at him out of the corner of his eye, "...From my perspective, yes." "So then, I should just, what, try walking downstairs instead?" Oliver balks. "That might work." Kogan nods, but he's still staring off into space with a slight pinch to his features that tells Oliver he's holding something back. "...Unless?" Oliver asks, clenching his jaw. "Unless — and this does seem more likely given... *everything*... — the staircase is trying to drive us mad. Either by turning us against each other as we argue over the true direction of the stairs or... Or the stairs may continue on indefinitely until one of us..." Kogan's eyes flick up to Oliver's for a moment before dropping to his own clasped hands, "succumbs."

13:53:55

"Well..." Oliver bows his head, "isn't that a nice thought..." He lets out a long breath and closes his eyes. It was no secret who was having a harder time on the stairs. It was probably for the best, Oliver told himself. He doubted Kogan would have any trouble going on without him. Oliver, on the other hand... He tried to imagine losing Kogan here; he could barely stand the thought of it. If one of them wasn't going to make it, it was better for everyone if it was Oliver. A shudder seemed to run through the staircase then, which, for reasons he couldn't explain, made Oliver think of laughter. Oliver peeks down at Kogan. The smaller man's shoulders are tense, and he has a slightly wild look in his eyes as he stares straight ahead. Kogan's knuckles have gone white from how tightly he's clasping his hands, and Oliver thinks he sees a slight tremor in them. "Hey," Oliver says, placing a hand on Kogan's shoulder, causing his friend's narrow frame to dip slightly under the weight. "We can do this. Even if I have to carry you." He flashes Kogan a small smile that he hopes comes across as comforting despite how his heart clenches. Kogan glares up at him. Oliver prepares to be told off, but Kogan freezes, mouth open and eyes growing wide. Oliver is about to look over his shoulder to see if maybe God himself has appeared when Kogan suddenly jumps to his feet. "That could do it!" Kogan exclaims, grasping Oliver's hand that had been resting on his shoulder. "If we move as one, the stairs will only have one direction. We may be able to beat the illusion...!" With wide eyes, Oliver looks down to where their hands are connected and then back up at Kogan's expectant face. Oliver exhales and adopts a lopsided grin, "bridal carry or piggyback?" Kogan looks away and scowls, quickly returning to his usual prickly demeanor as Oliver rises to his feet. "I'm not sure how much good this will do..." Kogan says, frowning, "You could barely make it up the stairs on your own, let alone carrying another person." Oliver holds his arms out to Kogan. "We'll never know until we try." Oliver smiles to himself as Kogan climbs onto his back and clings to him with an iron grip. "It's okay," He says, wrapping his hands firmly under Kogan's knees. "I've got you." Truth be told, Oliver was nervous. He knew Kogan was right, and he wasn't sure how much further he could climb. So, just in case this was like one of those spinning illusions, Oliver takes a moment to focus on the idea that the stairs are DESCENDING, DESCENDING, DESCENDING. But nothing can prepare him for the disorienting shift of reality as his foot seems to fall through the space where he expected the next step to be, and gravity is pulling him down fast. From his back, Kogan yelps, arms shooting out and bracing on the steps above them as his legs squeeze around Oliver's waist, holding him upright and narrowly saving them both from a tumble down the stairs. "What happened?!" Kogan gasps, his voice pitched higher than usual. "Sorry!" Oliver squeaks, "I just... It worked! The stairs are going *down*!" A relieved huff of laughter bursts from Kogan, and Oliver can't help the grin that spreads across his face. Together, they descend another 500 steps or so until, finally, the maddening staircase appears to lose interest and releases them from its clutches.
